G. Braziller | 1976 | Pdf | Eng | ISBN10 0807607916 | 211 pag | 31.7 MB


&quot;The strongly compressed harvest of considerable research, this is a useful and  continuously enlightening history of American graphic arts from the time when Stephen Daye (more likely his son Matthew) became the first American printer, setting up a press in what is now Cambridge, Massachusetts, in 1639. Hornung and Johnson, deliberately by-passing the arts of painting and prints, have succeeded admirably in their limited aim. They trace in concise, well-balanced and accurate terms the development of American graphics through the earliest Colonial newspapers, almanacs, Franklin's contributions, William Caslon's types (used in the first printing of the Declaration), the &quot;Gothic revival&quot; and every technical innovation up to contemporary printing and its flourishing diversity as shown in advertising, photo reproduction, book design, poster art and much else.
Some three hundred illustrations help make this one of the finest single volumes available on the subject, and a good Bicentennial item.&quot;
